                  <additions>
                    <list>
                      <item xml:id = "a1">
                        <desc>
                          <locus target = "#153v"/> Prayer to Mary by the author whose name has been erased
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id = "a2">
                        <desc>
                        Overlooked words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target = "#43r #146r"/>);
                        and overlooked lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target = "#109v"/>);
                        and in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target = "#23v"/>, line 15).
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id = "a3">
                        <desc>
                        The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio
                        for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. This scribe will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line
                        (e.g., <locus target = "#1r #4r #7r #15r #18v"/>, etc.). When a line is still too long it is completed above or below the end of the line. In these cases,
                        the scribe places the material above the line (e.g., <locus target = "#3v #5r #8v #10r #12r #12v #14v #16r"/>, etc.), or below (e.g., <locus target = "#6r #10v #14v #16r #18r"/>, etc.).
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id = "e1">
                        <desc><locus target = "#i"/> cut out</desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id = "e2">
                        <desc>Back cover has tag with the following written: 1100– AF305</desc>
                      </item>
                    </list>
                  </additions>
